<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<ecoSpold xmlns="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02 ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02.xsd http://www.EcoInvent.org/UsedUserMasterData ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02UserMasterData.xsd">
  <childActivityDataset>
    <activityDescription>
      <activity specialActivityType="0" id="3f6392bc-63ed-53ad-997b-e32bc563c1be" activityNameId="68d151d5-0525-4ae7-a943-b66333f4d881" parentActivityId="ffaa7070-ab75-55ae-bc2b-90a70cff332e" inheritanceDepth="-1" type="1">
        <activityName xml:lang="en">petroleum and gas production, offshore</activityName>
        <includedActivitiesStart xml:lang="en">From exploration activities (e.g., fuel requirements and emissions from well testing). Production via conventional extraction methods for petroleum and natural gas, considering infrastructure inputs of the offshore platform and gas processing plants, energy requirements, auxiliary chemicals consumption, and emissions.</includedActivitiesStart>
        <includedActivitiesEnd xml:lang="en">The activity ends with the dried (processed) natural gas and the crude petroleum oil at shore, ready for long-distance transport (transmission) and/or distribution. Neither gas processing activities primarily intended for the production of natural gas liquids nor secondary liquid separation are considered. Transport of platforms to the destination (site of extraction) is not considered.</includedActivitiesEnd>
        <generalComment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">The multioutput process 'petroleum and gas production, offshore' delivers the co-products crude petroleum oil [kg] and natural gas [m3] via conventional extraction methods. Separate production of crude petroleum oil and natural gas (i.e., non-associated) is considered implicitly within this inventory, which is based on total output by country.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">The production of petroleum and/or natural gas in Ecuador in 2021 is modelled as 1.6 % offshore and 98.4 % onshore production following the approach described in Meili et al. (2023, section 4.1).</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">The dataset covers the environmental impact of extraction and delivery to coastal plant of petroleum and natural gas. It includes country-specific methane emissions (vented, fugitive, and from flaring), the discharge of produced water, and the direct energy use during oil extraction including drilling and flaring. Flaring is the controlled and intentional burning of natural gas as part of production and processing of crude oil and natural gas. Reasons for flaring include safety, economics (oil vs. gas price), disposal of gas of inferior quality, etc. Furthermore, emissions due to oil spills related with drilling and pumping operations are included in this inventory, but excluding spills related to transportation and refining. Amounts of oil spilled to sea (offshore) and river/soil (onshore) per kg oil-equivalent of production were derived for world regions from three-year averages based on IOGP 2022.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">The inventory for this combined crude oil and natural gas production activity is mainly allocated based on the net calorific values and the annual production volumes of the co-products. The allocation of methane emissions from venting and fugative natural gas emissions is based on the country-specific information for 2021 from IEA's Methane Tracker 2022. The IEA factors for oil and gas extraction are used directly to split the total emissions between natural gas and crude oil per country. Freshwater use and water discharge are allocated to crude petroleum oil only. The underlying inventory was created as described in Meili et al. (2023), using generic a gross calorific value (GCV) of 40MJ/m3, a net calorific value (NCV) of 36.0 MJ/m3 and a density of 0.735kg/m3 for natural gas, in line with the global statistics (referring to standard cubic meters, Sm3, measured at 15°C and 1013 mbar). A net calorific value of 43.4 MJ/kg is used for crude petroleum oil and related products like condensates and liquefied natural gas liquids, with the density of crude oil set to 858.1 kg/m3.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">Reference(s):</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">C. Meili, N. Jungbluth, M. Bussa (2023) Life cycle inventories of crude oil and natural gas extraction. ESU-services Ltd. Schaffhausen, Switzerland. Available from: http://esu-services.ch/data/public-lci-reports/</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">IOGP (2022) Environmental performance indicators - 2021 data. International Association of Oil and Gas Producers (IOGP), retrieved from: https://www.iogp.org/bookstore/product-category/environment/</text>
        </generalComment>
      </activity>
      <classification classificationId="ae94b54e-3d5e-4eb3-8c07-449b50bd1cee">
        <classificationSystem xml:lang="en">ISIC rev.4 ecoinvent</classificationSystem>
        <classificationValue xml:lang="en">06:Extraction of crude petroleum and natural gas</classificationValue>
      </classification>
      <geography geographyId="0d0e72a0-7d7e-11de-9ae2-0019e336be3a">
        <shortname xml:lang="en">EC</shortname>
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">Ecuador</text>
        </comment>
      </geography>
      <technology technologyLevel="3">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">This dataset represents the offshore extraction of petroleum and gas via conventional extraction methods. This includes the gas lift process and deep-pump pumping (see Meili et al., 2023, chapter 3.1), as well as a default share of 15% enhanced oil recovery (EOR; described in section 4.2 of Meili et al., 2023). For the natural gas production, also the processing of the gas (e.g., drying and desulfurization) is considered.</text>
        </comment>
      </technology>
      <timePeriod startDate="2021-01-01" endDate="2023-12-31" isDataValidForEntirePeriod="true">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">Time of most relevant publications and statistics. Other generic data, e.g. for infrastructure are based on older publications.</text>
        </comment>
      </timePeriod>
      <macroEconomicScenario macroEconomicScenarioId="d9f57f0a-a01f-42eb-a57b-8f18d6635801">
        <name xml:lang="en">Business-as-Usual</name>
      </macroEconomicScenario>
    </activityDescription>
